AB  - The Pelican boat-ramp site is located within Swansea Channel, which connects the Tasman Sea to Lake Macquarie, NSW. The Pelican shoreline is very active, despite a low energy wave climate, primarily caused by strong, shore parallel tidal currents, up to 1.5m/s, and the continuing, long-term morphological changes associated with entrance training in the late 1880s and continuing intermittent dredging of the channel for navigation purposes. Additionally, eastward migration of the thalweg, at least partly arising from these activities, steepens the Pelican shoreline and has caused a significant shoreline/underwater landslide at a site to the immediate north of the boat-ramp, as well as aggressive shoreline recession. Lake Macquarie Council closed the boat-ramp in 2016 as a result of shoreline damage at the site and the unsafe state of the facility. All of these processes required consideration in the re-design of the boat-ramp, and its foundations - the boat-ramp has been re-constructed recently. The new facility includes mooring pontoons on its southern and northern sides. They assist passenger embarkation/dis-embarkation in the strong tidal current regime, as well as providing some shelter from prevailing wave conditions. Â© Australasian Coasts and Ports 2019 Conference. All rights reserved.
