AB  - The Channel Tunnel Rail Link (CTRL) will connect London's St. Pancras Station and the Channel Tunnel with a new, 109 kilometre, high speed railway. Its alignment to the east of London is across the Thames Marshes. The marshes are typical of low-lying areas now protected by tidal defences. Networks of natural and man-made rivers and ditches, which receive up-catchment flows and provide local drainage, cross the land and discharge via several tidal gates into the River Thames. Preliminary assessments identified that flooding through this area may seriously disrupt the rail service, with tunnel and track inundation, rail wash out and signal and communications failure, causing suspension of service for up to six months and over a hundred million pounds of damage. To assess the flooding risk to the CTRL, and to provide information on how its construction could affect river flows and levels, an in-depth assessment has been undertaken of the complex hydrological and hydraulic characteristics of the area. This has encompassed the appraisal of a variety of records, for a 30 square kilometre study area. Hydraulic modelling has highlighted railway flood defence requirements and has been used to assess proposed hydraulic mitigation and cross drainage designs. Conclusions have also been drawn from the study on how the overall hydraulic regime operates in low-lying areas protected from the tide. This is an increasingly important issue as the impacts of global warming may mean a rise in sea levels, and a change in climatic conditions causing more frequent flood events.
