AB  - A key strategy of the New Zealand Ministry of Foreign Affairs and Trade (MFAT) Development Programme in Vanuatu is a focus on lifting economic performance through investments in tourism, inter-island shipping infrastructure and services, potable water supply and solar power for rural communities. One of these aid streams targets development of public infrastructure to enhance tourism growth. Cruise ship tourism is of particular importance, as arrivals have increased by about 150 per cent between 2006 and 2012 and cruise ship visitors continue to supply the highest number of visitors in the sector in Vanuatu, accounting for 56% of total international visitors. The Vanuatu Tourism Infrastructure Project aims to improve infrastructure at the Port and Seafront Precincts in Port Vila, thereby enhancing the visitor experience and encouraging return visits. The public infrastructure improvements will also enhance the livelihoods and Seafront Park experience for ni-Vanuatu. The project upgrades and rehabilitates sections of the Port Vila waterfront and is driven by landscape architecture and building architecture in local context. This paper describes the issues in coordination and development of the landscape and building architecture themes, which are the prime drivers of the project, whilst still meeting engineering best practice and standards for coastal structures, coastal edge protection and jetty structures.
