AB  - Ongoing efforts by the federal government to promote coastal resilience have focused on critical infrastructure, natural and nature-based infrastructure, post-disaster recovery actions, community risk assessments, and the prioritization of resources. Such resilience can be characterized as a given coastal community's ability to respond to and recover from a disruption, such as a severe hurricane, nuisance flooding, or even long-term sea-level rise. For ocean engineers and community leaders alike, the operationalization of resilience requires the ability to collect, organize, process, and analyze real-world data from routinely disrupted communities. Modern systems engineering techniques and associated architecture frameworks are well suited for the characterization of coastal resilience. Ultimately, the added value of using systems engineering to operationalize coastal resilience data is significant: with a clear, understandable architecture framework in place, one can better explore the precise factors that allow a complex system to be resilient. For technical and political decision makers, resources can be better allocated to the system components, subsystems, or operations that best support a robust response and recovery.
