JO  - Geographical Journal
PY  - 1998
VL  - 164
IS  - 3
AB  - Insurance against natural perils such as flooding can be regarded as a significant element within coastal zone management. Not only does it offer much-needed support to accelerate economic and social recovery following a disaster (coastal resilience), but it can also contribute to impact limitation by using pricing or restrictions on availability of cover to discourage new development in hazard-prone areas. Although the basic principles are well-established and general, the practice of natural hazard insurance differs significantly between those countries (such as the UK) where the insurance market is commercial, and those (such as the USA) where government plays a major role in the provision of insurance. By exploring the nature of risk, it is possible to understand how these two models meet the needs of society in different ways. Underlying the role of insurance is the probabilistic nature of the risk prediction, and this changes as hood data become more precise. It is argued that care will be needed to evolve the structure of the commercial insurance market, and perhaps its relationship with government and planners, if provision is to remain robust and socially-beneficial when the uncertainty in the prediction is reduced. At the same time, as insurers come to appreciate the key role that they play in buffering society against periodic catastrophic environmental impacts, they are increasingly mounting a global lobby to encourage positive action to constrain global climatic change.
