TY  - Conference
TI  - Coastal zone management plans-the need to balance all costs and benefits
JO  - Australian Coasts And Ports 2015 Conference
PY  - 2015
VL  - NA
IS  - NA
AB  - Climate change and sea level rises pose a huge threat to the Australian "way of life" and the national economy. The problems are vast but coastal management plans are generally prepared and implemented at the local government level with limited resources. Australian local authorities preparing Coastal Management Plans are usually required by State Policies to achieve, at least in theory, a balance between the conservation of the natural resources of the beach environment and the protection of man-made resources, economy, community and infrastructure. Adding sea level rise introduces complexity and uncertainty that is not well addressed by governments. Benefit Cost Analysis are an important planning tool included in the evaluation of options in most coastal management plans. Ideally, these analyses should quantify coastal environmental values, cultural heritage values and the economic wellbeing of the community as well as the more easily measured financial estimates of beach related economic activity and property values. Most coastal management plans consider only financial issues and some recent Coastal Zone Management Plans developed by NSW local government authorities have meet with reactions from local communities that indicates a dissatisfaction or misunderstanding of the processes. The approaches and experiences of 4 very different east coast coastal communities, Gold Coast, Byron Bay, Old Bar and Seaforth have been compared and a number of trends have been identified. From the threats to our coastline and these trends, there is a need for significant paradigm shifts in the way coastal protection is evaluated, implemented and managed in Australia. In particular, Benefit Cost Analysis methods need to be expanded to better apportion costs and benefits between stakeholders to facilitate funding.
